<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Under the Bretton Woods system (1944-1971), which currency was directly convertible to gold?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">British Pound</option>
            <option letter="b">U.S. Dollar</option>
            <option letter="c">French Franc</option>
            <option letter="d">German Mark</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Only the U.S. dollar was directly convertible to gold at $35 per ounce. Other currencies were pegged to the dollar.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What is currency appreciation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">When a currency becomes worth more relative to other currencies</option>
            <option letter="b">When a currency becomes worth less relative to other currencies</option>
            <option letter="c">When inflation increases the money supply</option>
            <option letter="d">When a country increases interest rates</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Currency appreciation occurs when a currency increases in value relative to other currencies, making foreign goods cheaper and domestic goods more expensive.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What typically happens to a country's exports when its currency appreciates?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Exports increase</option>
            <option letter="b">Exports decrease</option>
            <option letter="c">Exports stay the same</option>
            <option letter="d">Exports become more volatile</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When a currency appreciates, the country's exports become more expensive to foreign buyers, typically leading to decreased exports.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which organization was created at Bretton Woods to help maintain exchange rate stability?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">World Trade Organization</option>
            <option letter="b">International Monetary Fund</option>
            <option letter="c">European Central Bank</option>
            <option letter="d">Bank for International Settlements</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The International Monetary Fund (IMF) was established at Bretton Woods to help maintain stable exchange rates and assist countries with balance of payments problems.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What is meant by a "flexible" or "floating" exchange rate system?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Exchange rates are fixed by government decree</option>
            <option letter="b">Exchange rates are determined by market forces</option>
            <option letter="c">Exchange rates are tied to gold</option>
            <option letter="d">Exchange rates are managed by central banks only</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>In a flexible or floating exchange rate system, currency values are determined by supply and demand in the foreign exchange market rather than being fixed by governments.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
